{ Hi guys! Welcome to another opening study! Today, we will tackle the Reti Opening.

What is the Reti Opening? It starts with white playing Nf3 on the first move. I will tackle everything that black can do against it.

The main idea of this opening is to transpose into a completely different opening or play an independent line.

I will show you some transpositions into some other lines and the King's Indian Attack!

Let's get straight into action! }
 *


[Event "The IMPENETRABLE Reti Opening: Chapter 1: Reti Opening vs King's Indian Defense"]
[Date "2026.05.31"]
[Result "*"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "A48"]
[Opening "London System, with Be2"]
[StudyName "The IMPENETRABLE Reti Opening"]
[ChapterName "Chapter 1: Reti Opening vs King's Indian Defense"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/iN61Eams/8HrTh1uU"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/mAtteoYOsef07"]
[UTCDate "2026.05.31"]
[UTCTime "01:54:43"]
[ChapterMode "gamebook"]

{ Play the Reti Opening. } { [%csl Gf3][%cal Gg1f3] }
1. Nf3 Nf6 { There are a million different moves you can play, but I recommend playing d4. } 2. d4 g6 { Play Bf4. } 3. Bf4 { We have now transposed into a London System. } 3... Bg7 { Push the pawn up to e3. } 4. e3 O-O { Develop the bishop to e2. } 5. Be2 d6 { Push the pawn up to h3. } 6. h3 { This simple pawn move is actually a very useful move. First, you want to give an escape square for your bishop to go to h2. Second, you want to prevent anything from going to g4. } 6... Nbd7 { Castle the king. } 7. O-O Qe8 { Instead of playing c3, c4 is more ambitious and sounder. } 8. c4 e5 { Retreat the bishop to h2. } 9. Bh2 Ne4 { Develop the knight to d2. } 10. Nbd2 Nxd2 { Recapture while developing. } 11. Qxd2 { You now have a decent position with queenside space. } *


