[Event "The IMPENETRABLE Reti Opening: Chapter 7: King's Indian Attack vs French Defense"]
[Date "2026.05.31"]
[Result "*"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "A08"]
[Opening "King's Indian Attack: Sicilian Variation"]
[StudyName "The IMPENETRABLE Reti Opening"]
[ChapterName "Chapter 7: King's Indian Attack vs French Defense"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/iN61Eams/YINe2k5E"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/mAtteoYOsef07"]
[UTCDate "2026.05.31"]
[UTCTime "13:10:17"]
[ChapterMode "gamebook"]

{ [%csl Bf3][%cal Bg1f3] }
1. Nf3 d5 { [%cal Bg2g3] } 2. g3 Nf6 { [%csl Bg2][%cal Bf1g2] } 3. Bg2 e6 { [%csl Bg1][%cal Be1g1] } 4. O-O c5 { [%cal Bd2d3] } 5. d3 Nc6 { [%csl Bd2][%cal Bb1d2] } 6. Nbd2 { This is our main setup. We castle the king, place the knights on f3 and d2, the pawns will be on d3 and g3 while your sniper is standing right there on g2. Our main pawn break is e4, but c4 can also be played. } { [%csl Rf2,Rg2,Rh2,Rg3,Rd2,Rd3,Rf3,Rf1,Rg1] } 6... Be7 { [%csl Be4][%cal Be2e4] } 7. e4! { Our main pawn break in the position! e4 has been played to gain central space. There is now central tension with the d5 and e4 pawns staring at each other! Black really shouldn't take on e4 because they lose central space and we just play dxe4, but as white, taking on d5 also looks like a bad move because we give up central space, but we have compensation for that because we have our rook on e1 that we be perfectly placed on the future open e-file. Everytime we take on d5, we follow that up with d4 only if they take with the pawn. If they take with the knight, they lose central space and we can even play Ne4 next move or even c4 followed by Nxc4 (their pawn will be on b5 sooner or later). Gaining central space with e5 is also good to kick away the f6 knight from the defense of the king and we will generate a kingside attack after that. } { [%csl Rf5,Rd5][%cal Re4d5,Re4f5] } 7... O-O { [%csl Be1][%cal Bf1e1] } 8. Re1 { d4 is a useless move because it weakens the c4 square and we can play a4! e5 is also possible to use the e4 square as a good outpost for the knight.
dxe4 is no problem because we just play dxe4 and they lost their powerful central pawn on d5. } 8... b5 { Push or take? } { [%csl Ge5,Rd5][%cal Ge4e5,Re4d5] } 9. e5 { Gaining space in the center and kicking the f6 knight away from the defense of their king. } { [%csl Rf6,Rd6][%cal Re5f6,Re5d6] } (9. exd5 { One of the best moves to follow it up with d4, this is an alternative we will cover. }) 9... Nd7 { [%csl Bf1][%cal Bd2f1] } 10. Nf1 b4 { [%csl Bh4][%cal Bh2h4] } 11. h4 a5 { [%csl Bf4][%cal Bc1f4] } 12. Bf4 { You want a kingside attack. } { [%csl Bh6,Rg4,Ge6][%cal Rf1h2,Rh2g4,Bh4h5,Bh5h6,Yf1e3,Ye3g4,Gg2h3,Gh3e6] } *


