1. Nf3 e6 { [%csl Yg3][%cal Yg2g3] } 2. g3 d5 { [%csl Bg2][%cal Bf1g2] } 3. Bg2 Nf6 { [%csl Bg1][%cal Be1g1] } 4. O-O c5 { [%csl Rd3][%cal Rd2d3] } 5. d3 Nc6 { Remember I said you can do two pawn breaks? You don't need to play Nbd2 and e4! You can just play c4! } { [%csl Gc4][%cal Gc2c4] } 6. c4! { It is even considered the engine's best choice! } (6. Nbd2 { Good move, but you are studying the move c4 for a moment and you already studied this move. }) 6... d4 { This is the point. We provoke them to push so we can undermine their structure with e3. } { [%csl Ye3][%cal Ye2e3] } 7. e3 Be7 { [%csl Yd4][%cal Ye3d4] } 8. exd4 cxd4 { Develop the knight to a3 and place it on c2. } { [%csl Bc2][%cal Bb1a3,Ba3c2] } 9. Na3 { You are not worried of doubling your a-pawns because it is actually good for you because you get the bishop pair and the open b-file. } { [%csl Bc2][%cal Ba3c2] } (9. Nbd2?! { No, no, no, not to this square. }) (9. Nc3?? { Hangs the knight!!! }) (9. Re1 { Uhh... this is good but play Na3 to continue. }) (9. Ne5?? { No, no... not this one }) (9. Bh6?? { No, no... not this one }) (9. Nxd4??) (9. a3 { Ok, decent, but not the best. } { [%csl Rb4][%cal Rb2b4] }) 9... O-O { [%csl Bc2][%cal Ba3c2] } 10. Nc2 { Do you know what your knight is doing here? First of all, it controls the important d4 square which makes e5 followed by e4 harder to do because d4 gets weak. Second, you prepare you expansion with b4 which is your main plan in the position. Pretty creative idea isn't it? } 10... e5 { [%csl Ye1][%cal Yf1e1] } 11. Re1 { Double pressure on the pawn. Hmm... } { [%csl Re5][%cal Re1e5,Rf3e5] } 11... Bd6 { Well... guess what? We can now play b4.... wait what? Isn't that pawn hanging? Wait a minute... their e5 pawn hangs! We can safely play b4 without any problems! } { [%csl Bb4][%cal Bb2b4] } 12. b4! Nxb4 { [%csl Yb4][%cal Yc2b4] } 13. Nxb4 Bxb4 { [%csl Be5][%cal Be1e5] } 14. Rxe5 { Ya' can't take with the knight sadly because your rook hangs, but this is fine. } (14. Nxe5?? { Oh no... } { [%csl Re1][%cal Rb4e1] }) 14... Bc3 { [%csl Bb1][%cal Ba1b1] } 15. Rb1 $18 { White is literally +1.0 in this position but I think it's even more due to the weak d4 pawn and the queenside pressure. Your bishop on g2 is a sniper! It snipes the whole diagonal that black can't even move!
Just get rid of the c3 bishop and target the d4 pawn to convert it into a win! Look at your pieces, they are extremely active that black can easily fall apart. They can't even develop their bishop because b7 hangs and if they try to fianchetto it, they will have problems on the long diagonal due to our monster bishop on g2!
Next chapter... } *


